experimental_relax_shapes when True, tf.function generates fewer, graphs that are specialized on the input sizes.

From commit message " Pull iterator advancement out of the tf.function loops, its not supposed to work there. Even if it was working just fine... this seems slightly faster." TensorFlow Federated (TFF) is an open-source framework for machine learning and other computations on decentralized data. TFF has been developed to facilitate open research and experimentation with Federated Learning (FL), an approach to machine learning where a shared global model is trained across many participating clients that keep their training data locally. 

tff.tf_computation: Decorates/wraps Python functions and defuns as TFF TensorFlow computations. These are sections of TensorFlow code wrapped as reusable components in TFF using the tff.tf_computation decorator. They always have functional types, and unlike functions in TensorFlow, they can take structured parameters or return structured results of a sequence type.

In tf.function only supports creating variables once, when first called, and then reusing them. You cannot create tf.Variables in new traces. Creating new variables in subsequent calls is currently not allowed, but will be in the future.

They insert a `tf.function` decorator before (underneath) the
`tff.tf_computation` decorator, and enter a `tf.init_scope` context during
`tf.Variable` creation. The `tf.init_scope` hoists variable creation out of the
`tf.function` to the nearest graph scope (provided by `tff.tf_comptuation`),
which would otherwise result in an error from the the `tf.function` wrapper.

TensorFlow Function has a few limitations by design that you should be aware of when converting a Python function to a Function (from https://bit.ly/2Sh6T4Y).

Side effects, like printing, appending to lists, and mutating globals, can behave unexpectedly inside a Function, sometimes executing twice or not all. They only happen the first time you call a Function with a set of inputs. Afterwards, the traced tf.Graph is re-executed, without executing the Python code.

The general rule of thumb is to avoid relying on Python side effects in your logic and only use them to debug your traces. Otherwise, TensorFlow APIs like tf.data, tf.print, tf.summary, tf.Variable.assign, and tf.TensorArray are the best way to ensure your code will be executed by the TensorFlow runtime with each call.

If your Function is not evaluating correctly, the error may be explained by these known issues which are planned to be fixed in the future. (from https://www.tensorflow.org/guide/function#known_issues)

input_signature: A possibly nested sequence of tf.TensorSpec objects specifying the shapes and dtypes of the Tensors that will be supplied to this function.
